english:
  title: Inscription on the Small Simplified Armillary Sphere
  author: Byeon Gyeyeong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    When Yao of Tang held dominion over the world, he first commanded Xi and He to establish the sundial correctly. From that time onward, through the ages, each era possessed its own instruments, yet it was only under the Yuan that they became complete. In the sixteenth year of the present reign, in autumn, the sovereign commanded Li Zhuo, Zheng Zhao, and Zheng Linzhi to craft a small simplified armillary sphere. Though it follows ancient designs, it truly emerges from new principles.

    The base is fashioned from refined copper, its rim encircled by water channels to establish perfect level. Thus the meridian lines find their proper place. Upon the celestial equatorial ring are inscribed the degrees of the celestial sphere, rotating east and west to measure the seven celestial bodies. The inner and outer officials mark the degrees where the stars lodge. The hundred-mark ring sits within the equatorial ring, its face divided into twelve hours and hundred marks—by day it reveals the sun's shadow, by night it fixes the central stars.

    The four-position ring, holding its sighting tube, rotates east and west, tilting north and south to await observation. A column stands to pierce through the three rings. When tilted obliquely, the four-position ring aligns with the north pole, the equator with heaven's belly. When set vertically, the four-position becomes the meridian frame and the hundred marks become the celestial latitude.

    When the work was scarcely complete, the ministers requested an inscription be carved to transmit to posterity. The king commanded Minister Zhao to compose it. I bow and present this inscription:

    Heaven's Way moves without motion,
    Instruments too prize simplicity.
    The ancient armillary sphere—
    its frame stood upon framework, layered thick.
    Yet this new instrument here,
    can be held and carried in hand.
    In its practical application,
    it serves the same purpose as the armillary sphere:
    indeed, a refinement of simplicity,
    simplified once again.
  footnotes:
    - The 'seven celestial bodies' (七政) refer to the sun, moon, and five visible planets in traditional Chinese astronomy.
    - The hundred-mark ring (百刻環) divides the day and night into 100 equal marks, a refinement over earlier timekeeping methods.
    - This inscription celebrates the innovation of creating a portable yet fully functional astronomical instrument—advancing from the fixed, complex armillary spheres of earlier times.
